    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_45203">D&amp;amp;D 'source code' <br />
<br />
That's the detail underpinning all mechanics within the D&amp;amp;D/d20 world.<br />
<br />
How combat works in particular in D&amp;amp;D:<br />
<br />
Armor class (defense value) = 10 + armor bonuses + dexterity bonuses (+ other bonuses that aren't important now)<br />
<br />
That is the target roll that you want to make on a 20 sided die to hit the baddie.  If their AC is 18, then you need to roll an 18 or better to hit.<br />
<br />
Your attack roll is modified by, among other things:<br />
<br />
BAB - Base attack bonus.  Fighters and their ilk get +1 to hit for every level, and an extra attack every 5.  Other classes get their bonuses less frequently than every level.<br />
<br />
Strength bonus - (Strength-10)/2 is the bonus to hit and bonus to damage (1.5 that amount if you use a 2 handed weapon)<br />
<br />
So returning to the above example, say you have a BAB of 3 and a strength bonus of 3 (from a 16 strength).  That means your modifiers are +6, and you need to roll a 12 on the d20 to hit the AC 18.<br />
<br />
There are other modifiers, such as magic weapons, etc, that aren't important.<br />
<br />
Each weapon does a certain amount of damage.  1-4, 1-6, 1-8, 2-8, or whatever.  Most simple weapons have crappy damage and critical hit (double damage) only on 20.  Martial weapons either make the damage better or increase the critical threat range (to 19-20).  Exotic weapons do both, but you need to spend a feat to be able to wield them appropriately.<br />
<br />
So, you swing stabble the above guy with your dagger.  You roll your 12 and hit (modified to hit roll of 1 , and then do 1-4 damage, plus your strength bonus.  So you do 4-7 damage with the dagger after taking your strength into account.<br />
<br />
Again, there are other modifiers, such as magical weapons.<br />
<br />
Stay away from the FAQ.  It's a bunch of jury rigged answers to questions because they didn't playtest the rules well enough, and some of the rules can be pretty crazy.  Stick to the SRD. </div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
