    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_45213">I find it rather funny that you say dual wield isn't worth it because of the feats...and then suggest that it's only worth it for those that pump an additional 4 feats into it and limit yourself to small weapons.  For me, it's typically the dex or a roleplaying decision that discourages me from going dual wield, not the feats.  Going from 12 to 14 (assuming most heavy plate types go for 12 dex due to +1 to hit with bows, +1 ac even in plate), and one more during levelling.  The weapon spec ones I might take for RP reasons, but I hate tieing myself down to certain weapon types.<br />
<br />
Added to that, other things take feats as well to set up properly.  For example, 2h works best when backed up by the same specialization stuff as well as power attack and cleave.  With the second power attack and greater cleave, you can clean up a room of trash real fast, and it's nice for chopping up chests.  But against non-easy opponents, you won't use it.  At the very least though, you want the first power attack and cleave.  Sword and board, on the other hand, is more likely to take specialization type feats, to make up for the lower damage.<br />
<br />
The whole tough opponents thing isn't that big of a deal either.  For starters, it's not tough opponents that matter.  It's hard to hit or damage reduction.  An opponent that's tough because of the damage they do or the hit points they have, the -2 doesn't bother the dual wielder.  What matters on those is killing faster and dual wield has the edge there.  For those where it is hard to hit, just put away the second weapon in favor of a shield.  That leaves DR mobs.  For those, well, you can go the higher crit chance route (assuming immunity or lack of fire/acid/lightning/sonic type damage) or bring out a 2h weapon.  Or else use potions/spells, kick in barb rage, whatever.<br />
<br />
As to damage, 2h doesn't compare when you figure in the damage adds.  A d6 of acid on one, 2d6 of fire on another, this sort of thing quickly tips the scales in favor in dual wield.  These things aren't scaled.  It's not like 1h weapons get 1d6 while 2h get 2d6.  Both get the same and since these things basically don't exist in the PnP D&amp;amp;D, dual wield isn't balanced with it in mind.  <br />
<br />
Differs by world, of course.  Bioware's world is pretty heavy with the additional damage.  Other worlds might rely more on traditional DnD weapons, maybe with 1 point of fire or whatever damage.  And other ones still are magically scarce.  Got to adapt to where you are.  Basically, for Bioware's modules and ones like those, I like dual wield.  For others, I typically don't bother.<br />
<br />
Anyway, they all have their ups and downs.  Works out about equally, although some things combined can be pretty vicious, weapons like kamas that have a big threat range and a big crit modifier, combined with being Keen and then feats to improve crits further.  But that has a lot more to do with the weapon than the fighting style.  If you had a great axe like weapon with a kamas crit stats, well...<br />
 <i>Edited by: Axterix EnObelix at: 12/11/03 3:05 pm<br />
</i></div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
